Data

Were using ggplot to visually explore global trends in public health and economics compiled by the Gapminder project. This project was pioneered by Hans Rosling, who is famous for describing the prosperity of nations over time through famines, wars and other historic events with this beautiful data visualization in his 2006 TED Talk: The best stats youve ever seen.



Loading and subsetting the data:

library(dslabs) #install.packages("dslabs")
library(tidyverse)

gap2011 <- gapminder %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  filter(year == 2011)

Life expectancy

ggplot(data = gap2011, mapping = aes(fertility, life_expectancy, color = continent)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~continent)

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(continent, life_expectancy))

Fertility

ggplot(data = gap2011, mapping = aes(fertility, infant_mortality, color = continent, size = population)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = gdp/population, infant_mortality, color = continent))
